"""
MKT Context Commentary — Proverbs chapters 7–9
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-proverbs-7-9.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/proverbs.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/proverbs.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/mkt-context/proverbs.json (existing chs 1–3)

Key context decisions:
- Ch 7 is the longest narrative poem in the prologue; its extended scene-setting
  (teacher at the window, twilight, her backstory) situates it as a case-study in
  the abstract warnings of chs 1–5. The fellowship-offering detail (v. 14) is
  specifically noted: it creates a window of permitted meat-eating that expires,
  adding urgency to the seduction.
- Ch 8:22–31 (Wisdom's pre-creation speech) is the theological climax of the
  prologue; the text's deliberate ambiguity about whether Wisdom is created or
  eternally present is noted without forcing a resolution.
- Ch 9's diptych (Wisdom's feast / Folly's invitation) frames the entire prologue's
  choice. The seven pillars (v. 1) are contextualised without imposing a single
  referent.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

PROVERBS = {
  "7": {
    "1": '<p>Chapter 7 opens the most extended narrative poem in Proverbs\' prologue — a dramatic scene-study that renders concrete the abstract warnings of chapters 1–5. The father\'s command to store his words "within you" (<em>ʾitti</em>, with me/inside yourself) continues the Deuteronomic language of internalizing instruction (Deut 6:6). The imperative to "keep my words" echoes covenant-loyalty vocabulary; wisdom instruction is presented as a personal covenant between father and son.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The "apple of your eye" (<em>ʾîšôn bat-ʿênekā</em>, literally "the little man of the daughter of your eye") is the Hebrew idiom for the pupil — the most delicate and vital part of the eye, instinctively protected. Using it for wisdom\'s teaching gives the instruction a bodily urgency: guard it as you guard your sight itself. The command to "keep my teaching" (<em>tôrātî</em>) deploys the same word used for the Mosaic Torah, placing parental wisdom instruction within the larger framework of divine law-giving.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The instruction to "tie them on your fingers" and "inscribe them on the tablet of your heart" (<em>lûaḥ libbeka</em>) directly alludes to the covenant command of Deut 6:8–9 and 11:18–20 (and cf. Jer 31:33\'s new covenant promise). The tablet (<em>lûaḥ</em>) is the inscribed stone of Sinai; wisdom commands the same kind of writing, but on the body\'s interior. In ancient Israel, physical objects (phylacteries, doorpost inscriptions) made commands spatially present; Proverbs internalizes that presence into the heart.</p>',
    "4": '<p>Calling Wisdom "my sister" (<em>ʾāḥôt</em>) and understanding "my closest companion" (<em>moddāʿ</em>, an intimate kinsman) is family-bond language; the Hebrew <em>moddāʿ</em> denotes a close relative who bears relational obligations (cf. Ruth 2:1 of Boaz). In the ancient Near East, one married within the extended kin group; calling Wisdom "sister" signals the most intimate possible bond while naming a relationship that guards against the sexual stranger. The personification of Wisdom as a protective kin-figure counters the personification of Folly as a seductive stranger.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The function of the wisdom-sister is protective: she "will keep you from" (<em>lišmārekā mê-</em>) the strange woman and the seductive stranger (<em>nokrîyyâ</em>, foreigner). The Strange Woman (<em>ʾiššâ zārâ</em>) of chapters 1–9 is the antithesis of Woman Wisdom — both are personifications, both call out to the young man. The "flattering words" (<em>ḥălāqâ</em>, smooth, slippery speech) of the stranger recall the adulteress of 2:16 and 5:3 whose lips "drip honey" but whose path leads to Sheol. Ancient Near Eastern wisdom literature (Egyptian and Mesopotamian) similarly warns against the dangerous woman as the primary threat to the young man\'s formation.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The narrative frame shifts in v. 6 to autobiographical reporting: "Once at the window of my house I looked out through the lattice." The window-lattice (<em>ʾešnab</em>) is the screened aperture of Iron Age Israelite domestic architecture; it allows observation while maintaining privacy. The teacher becomes an eyewitness narrator — a technique that gives moral instruction the authority of lived experience rather than abstract precept. Comparable scenes appear in Egyptian wisdom literature (<em>Instruction of Amenemope</em>; <em>Papyrus Insinger</em>), where the teacher also claims observed experience.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The observer spots "among the naive" (<em>pətāʾîm</em>, the open-minded simple who have not yet committed to wisdom or folly) a young man described as <em>ḥăsar-lēb</em> (lacking heart/mind — the same phrase as the "senseless" of 24:30). He is unformed, making him the ideal dramatic subject for the lesson: his choice is still open. In ancient Israel\'s social world, young men\'s formation — before they established households of their own — was the explicit target audience of the entire wisdom tradition.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"Cutting through the street near her corner, heading down the road toward her house" — the spatial detail is morally diagnostic. The youth is not there by accident; <em>šōʿeh</em> (heading, marching, going purposefully) implies direction, not wandering. The "corner" (<em>pinnāh</em>) where the Strange Woman stations herself is the public intersection — a place of maximum foot traffic in ancient cities, where commerce, gossip, and solicitation all occurred. The movement toward "her house" (<em>bêtāh</em>) narrows the frame: the house is the destination of no return (v. 27).</p>',
    "9": '<p>The time-stamp is dense: "twilight" (<em>bên hā-ʿarbayim</em>, between the two evenings), "evening" (<em>ʿereb</em>), and "the black darkness of night" (<em>ʾîšôn laylâ wă-ʾăpēlâ</em>). Darkness in ancient Israelite culture was the time of moral disorder, of those who "hate the light" (Job 24:13–17); lawful commerce and community life happened by day at the gate. Moving toward her house in deepening darkness is moving out of the world of wisdom and covenant and into the domain of death. The three-fold darkness intensifies the danger with each phrase.</p>',
    "10": '<p>"A woman met him, dressed like a prostitute, her heart scheming" — the clothing (<em>šît zônâ</em>, dress/attire of a prostitute) is the visual signal of her public availability; but "her heart scheming" (<em>nəṣurat lēb</em>, literally "guarded/crafty of heart") reveals that her inner life is concealed, calculating. The prostitute\'s dress code in Iron Age Israel may be referenced here; some scholars note that veils and specific garments signaled status (cf. Gen 38:14–15 of Tamar). The external display masks an internal agenda, making her doubly deceptive.</p>',
    "11": '<p>"She is loud (<em>hômiyyâ</em>, tumultuous, noisy) and defiant (<em>sōrāret</em>, rebellious, stubborn)" — these are opposite the qualities of the ideal woman of chapter 31 and the self-controlled wife of chapter 12. <em>sōrāret</em> (from <em>sārar</em>, to be stubborn) is used of Israel\'s covenant rebellion (Jer 5:23; Hos 4:16); applied to the Strange Woman, it casts her behavior as a species of apostasy from right order. "Her feet never stay at home" — the house (<em>bayit</em>) is the locus of Israelite female domestic honor; her constant movement outside it violates social-moral expectations of the day.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The description of her as "now outside, now in the streets, lurking at every corner" creates a spatial omnipresence that mirrors the description of Woman Wisdom\'s public proclamation (8:1–3; 9:1–3). Both figures inhabit public space; the difference is their posture — Wisdom calls openly from the high ground and the gates, while the Strange Woman lurks (<em>ʾārab</em>, to lie in wait, to ambush) at corners. The same verb <em>ʾārab</em> is used of military ambush (Josh 8:2, 4); the seductive woman is a predator, not simply a temptress.</p>',
    "13": '<p>"She grabbed him and kissed him" — the physical aggression is notable; typically in ANE literature it is the man who initiates physical contact. Here she is the pursuer. "Said to him with a brazen face" (<em>hēʿēzâ pānêhā</em>, she strengthened/hardened her face): a hardened face is the physical sign of shamelessness — the opposite of the blushing, modest face expected of Israelite women. Jeremiah uses the same phrase of Israel\'s shameless apostasy (Jer 3:3). Her boldness is covenant-defying.'
     + ' The kiss precedes the speech, establishing physical intimacy before the verbal seduction begins.</p>',
    "14": '<p>"I had fellowship offerings (<em>šəlāmîm</em>) to make; today I paid my vows" — this is a culturally specific detail that modern readers easily miss. The <em>šəlāmîm</em> (peace/fellowship offerings) were sacrificial meals at which the worshiper was required to eat the meat the same day or the next day (Lev 7:15–18). Having just offered sacrifices, she has a house full of fresh meat that must be consumed by nightfall — hence the urgency of her invitation. The sacrifice frames the seduction in religious terms: she has just been at the sanctuary, the religious legitimacy of the occasion covering the moral disorder of what follows.</p>',
    "15": '<p>"That is why I came out to meet you — I was looking for you and here you are" — the grammar of <em>wāʾimṣāʾekā</em> (I found you) uses the language of wisdom-seeking: in 8:17 Wisdom says "those who seek me will find me"; here the Strange Woman uses the same vocabulary of finding to describe her predatory searching. The language of earnest seeking is co-opted by seduction. Her claim that she specifically sought him personalizes the encounter and flatters the young man\'s sense of being specially chosen — a classic manipulation technique.</p>',
    "16": '<p>"Colored blankets and fine linen from Egypt" — the bed is prepared with imported luxury textiles. Egyptian linen was proverbially fine and expensive (cf. Prov 31:24); the display of Egyptian goods signals wealth, cosmopolitan sophistication, and access to long-distance trade networks. In the ancient Near East, luxurious bedding was a sign of high social status; the scene is designed to make the encounter seem an elevation in status for the young man. The exotic materials also carry a hint of the foreign — <em>nokrîyyâ</em> (foreign woman) is her designation — making Egypt part of the danger\'s texture.</p>',
    "17": '<p>Myrrh, aloes, and cinnamon — all imported aromatics used in perfumery, medicine, and sacred contexts. Myrrh (<em>mōr</em>) was used in the anointing oil of Exodus 30:23 and is the scent of the beloved in Song of Songs 1:13; 3:6; 4:14. Aloes (<em>ʾahālôt</em>) are aromatic wood from southeast Asia; cinnamon (<em>qinnāmôn</em>) is the bark of a Sri Lankan tree that entered ancient Mediterranean trade via Arabia and Phoenicia. The scent-palette is deliberately evocative of the erotic poetry of the Song of Songs — the Strange Woman uses the vocabulary of rightful love to frame illicit encounter.</p>',
    "18": '<p>"Come, let us drink our fill of love" (<em>nirweh dōdîm</em>, let us be saturated with loves/caresses) — <em>dôdîm</em> (plural of <em>dôd</em>, beloved, caresses) is the intimate vocabulary of the Song of Songs (1:2, 4; 4:10; 5:1; 7:12). The Strange Woman deliberately mirrors the language of the Song to make illicit love seem identical to rightful love — or perhaps more thrilling. "Until morning" implies an all-night encounter, the absence of her husband providing the window. The appeal is to pleasure, not commitment.</p>',
    "19": '<p>"My husband is not home" — the Hebrew <em>hāʾîš</em> (the man) is used rather than <em>baʿlî</em> (my lord/husband), a slightly distancing term. He "has gone on a long trip" (<em>derek merāḥôq</em>, a road far away) — the realities of Iron Age commerce required extended travel: merchants, officials, and craftsmen traveled trade routes that took weeks or months. The husband\'s absence on business is the social precondition for her availability. The detail authenticates the scenario culturally while providing the legal cover she deploys to reduce the young man\'s fear of being caught.</p>',
    "20": '<p>"He took his money with him" (<em>ṣərôr hakkesef lāqaḥ bəyādô</em>, he took the bag of money in his hand) — he is a merchant, a man of commerce, carrying capital. "He will not be back until the full moon" (<em>yôm hakkēse</em>) — a specific calendrical reference: the full moon (15th of the month in the lunar calendar) establishes a known window. She knows exactly how long she has. The specificity of the time-frame is the final detail that makes her case seem reasonable and risk-free — a calculated manipulation that uses the young man\'s economic rationality against him.</p>',
    "21": '<p>"With her many persuasive words she led him astray" — <em>liqḥāh</em> (she took him, she led him) is the same verb used of wisdom\'s instruction being "taken" or received (1:3; 8:10). The Strange Woman has her own form of pedagogy: an alternative wisdom education that re-routes the student toward death. Her words are described as <em>laqqāh</em> (convincing, persuasive — what wisdom also offers, 1:5; 4:2). The structural parallel is deliberate: seduction is a parody of wisdom-formation, using the same means toward opposite ends.</p>',
    "22": '<p>"He followed her at once — like an ox heading to slaughter, like a fool walking into punishment" — the animal similes domesticate the tragedy: the ox does not know it is heading to death; the young man is equally unknowing. The fool (<em>ʾěwîl</em>) walking into <em>musar</em> (discipline/punishment) — the very term for wisdom\'s corrective instruction — inverts it: what should lead to wisdom here leads to destruction. The similes belong to wisdom\'s characteristic mode of teaching by analogy, used here with bitter irony: the young man who should be learning from the animals is being compared unfavorably to them.</p>',
    "23": '<p>"Until an arrow pierces his liver" — the liver (<em>kābed</em>) was considered the seat of the emotions and inner life in ancient Mesopotamian physiology; to pierce the liver was the mortal wound. Divination was performed on animal livers (<em>haruspicy</em>), suggesting the liver\'s cosmological importance. The bird-and-snare image follows: the bird "does not know that his life is the price" (<em>bənap̄šô lō yēdāʿ</em>, he does not know it is for his life/soul) — <em>nephesh</em> here as the life-stake. The chapter that began with "keep my commands and live" (v. 2) ends with death as the cost of ignoring them.</p>',
    "24": '<p>The shift back to direct address (<em>ʾattā bānîm</em>, now, children) marks the end of the narrative and the opening of the application. The plural "children" broadens the address from the individual naive young man to the whole class of the teachable; the seduction-narrative has become a case-study for the group. "Pay close attention to what I am saying" (<em>qāšîbû ʾimrê-pî</em>, give ear to the words of my mouth) — the imperatives echo the opening of ch. 5 (5:1) and 8:6; the teacher\'s address-formula is itself a wisdom convention reaching back to Egyptian instruction texts.</p>',
    "25": '<p>"Do not let your heart wander toward her ways" — the heart (<em>lēb</em>) is the navigational organ in Proverbs; wisdom shapes it so that it chooses the right path instinctively. The command uses <em>yēšeṭ</em> (let it turn aside, wander; from <em>šāṭâ</em>) for the dangerous drift of the unguarded heart. "Do not go astray on her paths" — <em>tiʿû bənətîbôtêhā</em> (stray in her paths): the paths (<em>nəṭîbôt</em>) of the Strange Woman lead to death, just as wisdom\'s paths lead to life (cf. 3:17). The spatial metaphor that organizes the entire prologue — two paths, two destinations — reaches its climax here.</p>',
    "26": '<p>"She has brought down many victims; a long line of powerful men have been destroyed by her" — <em>rabbîm</em> (many) and <em>ʿăṣumîm</em> (strong, powerful) specify that it is not only the weak or foolish who fall: even the strong are not immune. This functions as the chapter\'s most sobering note: the naive young man of the narrative was merely one instance. Historical wisdom traditions recall heroes who fell to sexual temptation (Samson; Amnon) as warnings; the "powerful men" the Strange Woman has destroyed may gesture toward these known figures from Israel\'s story.</p>',
    "27": '<p>"Her house is the road to Sheol; it leads to the inner chambers of death" — the spatial journey that began in v. 6–9 (street → corner → her street → approaching her house) now reaches its terminus: her house is not a house at all but a road into the underworld. <em>Šəʾôl</em> (the realm of the dead) and <em>ḥadrê māwet</em> (inner rooms/chambers of death) form a chiasm with the opening of ch. 7: wisdom\'s commands lead to life (v. 2); the Strange Woman\'s house leads to death. The architectural image — house as passage into death — recurs in ancient Near Eastern myth (Inanna\'s descent through the gates of the underworld).</p>'
  },
  "8": {
    "1": '<p>Chapter 8 opens with a rhetorical question that begins Woman Wisdom\'s longest and most theologically dense speech in Proverbs. After ch. 7\'s portrait of the seductive stranger\'s darkness, ch. 8 sets Wisdom\'s open-air, public proclamation in sharp contrast. The two questions — "Does wisdom not call out? Does understanding not raise her voice?" — introduce Wisdom not as the silent ideal but as the public preacher. The historical context of wisdom-teaching in ancient Israel was the gate, the market, and the household; sages were public figures, not private tutors alone.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"She takes her stand on the high ground" (<em>bərāšê məromîm</em>, on the heights of the heights) — the elevated position is the position of public proclamation and authority; prophets and heralds spoke from heights. "At the crossroads where the paths meet" (<em>bêt nətîbôt niṣṣābâ</em>, where the paths converge she stands) — the crossroads is the site of maximum public traffic, where the greatest number of travelers can be reached. In deliberate contrast to the Strange Woman who "lurks at every corner" (7:12), Wisdom stands openly at the intersection of all paths.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"She cries out at the city gates" — the gate (<em>šaʿar</em>) was the civic heart of the Israelite city: the site of legal transactions, market exchange, judicial proceedings, and public assembly (Deut 25:7; Amos 5:12; Ruth 4:1–2). Wisdom preaching at the gate places her in the center of civic life, not at its margins. "At the entrance of the city, at the doorways" — the tripling of public locales (high ground, crossroads, gate entrance, doorways) emphasizes that Wisdom is everywhere that people circulate. She cannot be missed; choosing not to hear her is a deliberate act.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"I am calling to you — to all humanity" (<em>ʾălêkem ʾîšîm</em>, to you, O men) and "to every child of Adam" (<em>bənê ʾādām</em>) — Wisdom\'s address is explicitly universal, not restricted to Israel. The designation <em>bənê ʾādām</em> (children of humanity/Adam) places the call in the context of creational humanity rather than covenantal particularity; wisdom as a creational gift is addressed to all who bear the image of God. This universalism of wisdom\'s invitation distinguishes it from legal instruction specifically for Israel.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"You naive ones, learn prudence (<em>ʿormâ</em>)" — <em>pətāʾîm</em> (the simple, naive, open) are addressed first; they are the teachable middle — not yet wise, not yet hopelessly foolish. <em>ʿormâ</em> (prudence, shrewdness) is the positive form of the serpent\'s cunning (<em>ʿārôm</em>, Gen 3:1); wisdom rehabilitates cunning as legitimate practical intelligence. "You fools, gain a discerning heart (<em>lēb</em>)" — <em>kəsîlîm</em> (fools) are also addressed; even those who have drifted into habitual foolishness are called to turn. Wisdom\'s invitation is maximally inclusive in this opening address.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"Listen — I am speaking what is excellent" (<em>nəgîdîm</em>, excellent, princely things) — <em>nāgîd</em> is used of princes and leaders; Wisdom\'s words are the speech of royalty, not of commoners. "Everything from my mouth will be right" (<em>mîšār</em>, uprightness, what is level and straight) — the claim is absolute: no admixture of error or deception. The ancient Near Eastern wisdom tradition often attributed its teachings to royal figures or to divine inspiration; here Wisdom herself, as a quasi-divine figure, makes the claim of complete reliability for her own speech.</p>',
    "7": '<p>"My mouth speaks truth; wickedness is detestable to me" — Wisdom\'s self-description aligns her completely with YHWH\'s character. The word <em>tôʿăbâ</em> (abomination, detestable thing) used of wickedness vis-à-vis Wisdom echoes the many Proverbs passages where YHWH regards various behaviors as <em>tôʿăbâ</em> (11:20; 12:22; 15:8–9; 17:15). Wisdom\'s revulsion against wickedness is the same as God\'s revulsion — a further signal that Wisdom shares in the divine character and not merely in human prudence.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"Every word I speak is right; nothing I say is twisted or deceptive" — <em>kol-ʾimrê pî bəṣedeq</em> (all the words of my mouth are in righteousness) and <em>ʿiqquēš</em> (twisted, perverted) versus <em>pātaltôl</em> (crooked): the contrast between straight and twisted speech runs throughout the prologue. <em>ṣedeq</em> (righteousness) in wisdom contexts carries both the ethical sense (right conduct) and the cosmic sense (what is in proper alignment with the created order). Wisdom\'s speech is cosmologically straight — it conforms to the order built into creation.</p>',
    "9": '<p>"To those with understanding, my words are all clear (<em>nəkōḥîm</em>, right, plain, in front of one)" — clarity of wisdom\'s instruction is conditional on the hearer\'s formation; to those who have already pursued understanding, wisdom is plainly obvious. This is wisdom\'s pedagogical epistemology: the trained eye sees what the untrained cannot perceive. The historical practice in ancient Israel\'s wisdom schools (if they existed) would have involved progressive initiation into increasingly subtle instruction; Proverbs reflects this graduated transparency.</p>',
    "10": '<p>"Take my instruction rather than silver, and choose knowledge over the finest gold" — the economic comparison runs throughout the prologue (3:14–15; 8:18–19; 16:16). Wisdom in ancient Israel was not opposed to material wealth; the comparison works precisely because silver and gold are genuinely valuable. But wisdom is more valuable still. The wisdom schools of Egypt and Mesopotamia similarly elevated scribal learning and sage knowledge above mere accumulation; the scribal profession\'s prestige derived partly from its claim that wisdom exceeded wealth in practical utility.</p>',
    "11": '<p>"Wisdom is more valuable than precious gems" — <em>pənînîm</em> (precious corals or rubies — the exact identification is uncertain; a high-value gemstone) appears also in 3:15 and 31:10 (the capable wife). The comparison to gems places wisdom in the category of royal luxury; the point is not that gems are worthless but that they occupy the same category of supreme value, and wisdom exceeds them. "Nothing you could wish for compares to her" — the rhetorical hyperbole of pricelessness makes wisdom the ultimate comparatum: it is the standard against which all else is measured.</p>',
    "12": '<p>"I, wisdom, live alongside prudence" (<em>ḥokmâ šākanti ʿormâ</em>, wisdom — I dwell alongside prudence) — Wisdom now speaks in first person. <em>ʿormâ</em> (prudence, craftiness) is wisdom\'s practical expression; the two co-habit. "And find knowledge and good judgment" — <em>məzimmôt</em> (plans, deliberate thought) with <em>daʿat</em> (knowledge): Wisdom\'s household contains the full family of cognitive virtues. In Israelite wisdom anthropology, these were not abstract categories but practical capacities shaped through family and community formation — the "dwelling" of wisdom with prudence suggests a domestic training environment.</p>',
    "13": '<p>"The fear of the LORD means hating evil" — the fear of YHWH (the prologue\'s theological foundation, 1:7; 9:10) is defined here by its negative content: what it hates, not only what it loves. "Pride, arrogance, evil conduct, and perverse speech" — <em>gēʾâ</em> (pride, upward swelling) and <em>gāʾôn</em> (arrogance, exaltation) are paired; pride is the root sin in Proverbs (11:2; 16:18) and the prophets (Isa 2:11–17). "Perverse speech" (<em>taḥpukôt</em>, things that overturn, twisted inversions) closes the list — the corruption of right order through language. The fear of YHWH is as much an orientation of aversion as attraction.</p>',
    "14": '<p>"Mine are counsel (<em>ʿēṣâ</em>) and tested wisdom (<em>tûšiyyâ</em>)" — <em>tûšiyyâ</em> is a wisdom term that denotes effective, productive wisdom — wisdom that actually works in the world (cf. 2:7; 3:21; 18:1). "I am understanding; I have strength" — Wisdom claims not only cognitive but also executive capacity: <em>gebûrâ</em> (strength, might) is the attribute of warriors and kings. Wisdom is not merely theoretical knowledge but effective power over reality — the capacity to counsel and execute. This prepares for the claim that kings reign through Wisdom (v. 15).</p>',
    "15": '<p>"Through me kings reign and rulers issue just decrees" — the claim that political authority derives from Wisdom is ancient Near Eastern commonplace: Egyptian pharaohs were ideologically aligned with Maʿat (cosmic order/justice); Mesopotamian kings received wisdom from the gods. In Israel, Solomon\'s wisdom (1 Kgs 3:4–15; 4:29–34) is the primary model. The statement does not mean that all rulers are wise, but that legitimate authority — which produces just decrees (<em>ḥōqeq ṣedeq</em>, right statutes) — flows from Wisdom, whether rulers acknowledge this or not.</p>',
    "16": '<p>"Through me princes govern, and nobles — all who exercise righteous authority over the earth" — the governance claim extends from kings (v. 15) to the entire administrative class: princes (<em>śārîm</em>), nobles (<em>nədîbîm</em>), and all judges of the earth. In ancient Israel\'s administrative world, these would be the royal officials, tribal leaders, elders at the gate, and appointed judges who exercised authority under the Mosaic system. Wisdom claims to be the animating principle of all righteous governance — both a descriptive claim about good government and a normative call to those in authority.</p>',
    "17": '<p>"I love those who love me; those who seek me earnestly will find me" — <em>ʾōhăbay ʾāhāb</em> (those who love me I love) — the reciprocity of love between Wisdom and her followers is the positive counterpart to the Strange Woman\'s simulated love. <em>məšaḥărênî</em> (those who seek me earnestly) from <em>šāḥar</em> (to seek diligently, to seek at dawn) — early-morning seeking as the image of eager pursuit. In 7:15 the Strange Woman said she "was looking for" the young man; here Wisdom inverts the syntax: she is found by those who actively seek her. Wisdom is responsive, not elusive.</p>',
    "18": '<p>"With me are riches and honor — lasting wealth and righteousness" — Wisdom explicitly claims the material goods that the Strange Woman\'s seduction also promises (7:16–17). <em>ʿōšer</em> (riches) and <em>kābôd</em> (honor, glory) and <em>ṣədāqâ</em> (righteousness) — the triad of the wise person\'s reward (22:4). "Lasting wealth" (<em>hôn ʿātēq</em>) — <em>ʿātēq</em> denotes something tested, proven, seasoned; what Wisdom gives endures, unlike the transient pleasures of 7:18. In the economic culture of ancient Israel, lasting household wealth was the sign of divine blessing (Deut 28:1–14); Wisdom claims to be the path to covenantal prosperity.</p>',
    "19": '<p>"What I produce is better than gold — even fine gold" (<em>ḥārûṣ</em>, refined/choice gold); "my yield surpasses choice silver" — the agricultural vocabulary (<em>pərî</em>, fruit; <em>tənûbâ</em>, yield/produce) grounds Wisdom\'s wealth-claim in the creation order. Wisdom\'s "fruit" is a harvest — it grows and multiplies; gold and silver are static quantities. The contrast is between the accumulated capital of commerce and the renewable productivity of the created order — Wisdom belongs to the latter, participating in creation\'s own generative abundance.</p>',
    "20": '<p>"I walk in the path of righteousness, along the roads of justice" — Wisdom does not only teach a path; she walks it herself. <em>ōraḥ ṣədāqâ</em> (path of righteousness) and <em>nətîbôt mišpāṭ</em> (roads of justice) — the spatial metaphor that organizes the entire prologue is now claimed by Wisdom herself as her own habitat. <em>mišpāṭ</em> (justice, judgment) is the social-judicial ordering of community life; Wisdom inhabits the very territory of righteous social governance. Her walk is the model for the student\'s walk.</p>',
    "21": '<p>"Giving a real inheritance to those who love me, and filling their storehouses" — <em>naḥălâ</em> (inheritance) is Israel\'s most significant economic-theological category: the divinely allotted land-portion that defines the family\'s stake in the covenant community. Wisdom gives not just goods but an inheritance — a structural claim on the future. "Filling their storehouses" (<em>ʾôṣərôtêhem ʾămallēʾ</em>) — the storeroom or treasury as the sign of household prosperity. In an agrarian economy, a full storehouse was the difference between security and catastrophe; Wisdom\'s gift is existential stability.</p>',
    "22": '<p>"The LORD possessed me at the beginning of his way, before the oldest of his works" — v. 22 opens the most debated passage in Proverbs: Wisdom\'s account of her pre-creation origin (8:22–31). The verb <em>qānānî</em> (possessed me, created me, acquired me — from <em>qānâ</em>) has been contested across millennia: the LXX reads "created me" (<em>ektisen</em>), which shaped the Arian controversy of the 4th century. Whether <em>qānâ</em> here means "to create" (cf. Gen 14:19 of God creating heaven/earth) or "to possess/acquire" (cf. Deut 32:6) shapes how one reads Wisdom\'s relationship to the divine nature. The text is deliberately poised between these readings.</p>',
    "23": '<p>"I was installed from eternity — from the very beginning, before the earth existed" — <em>nīsakkôtî</em> (I was installed, poured out — from <em>nāsak</em>, to weave/install/anoint) is another contested term; it can suggest royal installation or being woven into the fabric of reality. "From eternity" (<em>mēʿôlām</em>) and "from the very beginning" (<em>mērōʾš miqqdmê-ʾāreṣ</em>, from the head, from the ancient times of the earth) place Wisdom\'s origin before creation itself. The temporal sequence — possessed/installed → before earth → before ocean → before mountains — is a kind of anti-genesis, narrating the pre-creation state.</p>',
    "24": '<p>"Before the oceans existed I was born" (<em>ḥôlāltî</em>, I was brought forth, birthed — from <em>ḥîl/ḥûl</em>, birth-labor) — the birth-language (<em>ḥôlāltî</em> in vv. 24, 25) is striking: Wisdom uses the vocabulary of being born, not merely created. Some ancient Near Eastern parallels (Ugaritic mythology; the Egyptian figure of Maʿat who existed before creation) illuminate this language. "Before the springs were teeming with water" — the primordial waters represent chaos before cosmic ordering (Gen 1:2); Wisdom existed before the primordial waters were filled with springs.</p>',
    "25": '<p>"Before the mountains were in place, before the hills, I was brought into being" — <em>qōdem gəbāʿôt ḥôlāltî</em>, before the hills I was born. Mountains and hills in the ancient Near East were cosmic fixed points — the oldest landmarks, the foundations of the world. Their pre-existence in common perception makes Wisdom\'s claim to antedate them all the more radical. The cosmological catalog is moving from the most primordial (ocean depths) to the most visibly fixed (mountains) — all of which postdate Wisdom.</p>',
    "26": '<p>"Before he had made the earth or its open lands (<em>ḥûṣôt</em>, its outside places/open fields) or the first dust of the world (<em>rōʾš ʿăpārôt tēbēl</em>)" — the "first dust" image may recall the dust from which Adam was formed (Gen 2:7); Wisdom precedes even the raw material of humanity\'s creation. <em>Tēbēl</em> (the inhabited world, the productive earth) is the earth as the domain of human civilization — Wisdom\'s existence precedes the very world she was given to guide. The pre-creation sequence reaches its final term: before the inhabited world itself.</p>',
    "27": '<p>"When he set the heavens in place I was there" — <em>bəhākînô šāmayim šām ʾānî</em>: <em>šām ʾānî</em> (there I was) — the emphatic placement. The act of "setting the heavens" (<em>hākîn</em>, establishing, fixing) corresponds to the cosmic-ordering work of Genesis 1. "When he drew the horizon over the face of the deep" (<em>bəḥûqqô ḥûg ʿal-pənê təhôm</em>) — the <em>ḥûg</em> (circle, horizon) drawn by the Creator corresponds to the divine compass used in creation; this image appears also in Isa 40:22 and Job 26:10 (God draws a circle on the face of the waters). Wisdom witnessed this act from alongside its Agent.</p>',
    "28": '<p>"When he fixed the clouds above and set firm the fountains of the deep" — the clouds (<em>šəḥāqîm</em>) and the fountains of the deep (<em>ʿênôt təhôm</em>) are the upper and lower boundaries of the cosmic water system; their establishment was the key act of creation that made habitable life possible. The "fountains of the deep" burst open in the flood (Gen 7:11; 8:2) and their restraint is what prevents the return of primordial chaos. Wisdom was present when these boundaries were established — making her the silent witness to the act that sustains all life.</p>',
    "29": '<p>"When he gave the sea its limits so the waters could not overstep his command" — <em>bəśûmô lāyām ḥuqqô</em> (when he set for the sea its decree/limit) — the sea\'s <em>ḥōq</em> (statute, limit, prescribed boundary) is the cosmic law that prevents chaos-waters from overrunning the earth (cf. Jer 5:22; Job 38:8–11; Ps 104:9). "When he marked out the earth\'s foundations" (<em>bəḥūqqô môsədê ʾāreṣ</em>) — the foundations of the earth are the unseen cosmic infrastructure; Wisdom witnessed their laying. The verse closes the cosmological survey: ocean-boundary and earth-foundation bracket the inhabitable world.</p>',
    "30": '<p>"Then I was beside him, the master craftsman (<em>ʾāmôn</em>)" — <em>ʾāmôn</em> is the crux of the entire passage; its meaning has been debated since antiquity. Three main proposals: (1) craftsman/artisan (from <em>ʾāman</em>, skilled work — so Wisdom was the demiurgic artisan alongside God in creation); (2) nursling/ward (Wisdom as the beloved child God was raising); (3) faithful one (from <em>ʾāman</em>, to be firm/faithful). The verse\'s context — "I was his daily delight, rejoicing before him always" — supports the nursling/child reading emotionally, but the craftsman reading best fits the creation context. The text may be intentionally polyvalent. "Rejoicing before him always" — <em>šāʿăšuʿîm</em> (delight, joy, playfulness) and <em>məśaḥeqet ləpānāyw</em> (playing/rejoicing before his face) — creation as the occasion of Wisdom\'s play, God\'s pleasure.</p>',
    "31": '<p>"Rejoicing in the world he had made, and my delight was in the children of humanity" — Wisdom\'s joy extends from God\'s presence to the created world and specifically to humanity. <em>bənê ʾādām</em> (children of humanity/Adam) — the same universal addressee as v. 4. The cosmological sweep of vv. 22–31 turns here toward human orientation: Wisdom delights in people, which is why she calls to them from the city gates. The pre-creation account is the backstory of the gate-proclamation: she who was there at creation\'s dawn now stands at the city gates calling humanity to the life she knew before creation began.</p>',
    "32": '<p>The return to direct address (<em>wəʿattā bānîm</em>, now therefore, children) closes the cosmological interlude and applies it: the pre-existent, creation-witnessing Wisdom speaks to you, now, in the city. "Blessed are those who keep to my ways" — <em>ʾašrê</em> (blessed, happy, to-be-congratulated) — the beatitude form beloved of the wisdom tradition (cf. Ps 1:1; 2:12; Prov 3:13; 8:34). Keeping Wisdom\'s ways is not merely prudential but genuinely the path to human flourishing as originally designed into creation.</p>',
    "33": '<p>"Accept instruction and be wise; do not reject it" — <em>liqḥû mûsārî</em> (receive my discipline/instruction) — the father\'s recurring command is now on Wisdom\'s own lips. "Do not reject it" (<em>ʾal-tipraʿû</em>, do not let go, do not break away) — <em>pāraʿ</em> means to let loose, to reject constraint (cf. Exod 32:25 of Israel running wild). Wisdom\'s instruction is a constraint that actually liberates; rejecting it produces the chaos of the unformed self. The command to receive instruction connects the cosmic Wisdom of vv. 22–31 to the practical pedagogy of the prologue\'s father-son discourses.</p>',
    "34": '<p>"Blessed is the person who listens to me — waiting at my doors every morning, watching at my threshold" — <em>lišqod ʾal-daltōtay yôm yôm</em> (keeping watch at my doors, day by day) — the image of the student as a devotee who waits at the teacher\'s door each morning was a reality in ancient wisdom education; Sirach describes sitting at the sage\'s feet (Sir 6:36–37). "Watching at my threshold" (<em>lišmōr məzûzōt pētāḥay</em>) — the doorpost (<em>məzûzâ</em>) is where Torah was commanded to be written (Deut 6:9); Wisdom\'s doorpost is where the student keeps watch. The spatial intimacy of the image elevates the student-wisdom relationship to near-covenantal proximity.</p>',
    "35": '<p>"Whoever finds me finds life and receives the LORD\'s favor" — the verb <em>māṣāʾ</em> (to find) appears also in 7:15 (the Strange Woman found the young man) and 18:22 (finding a wife). Wisdom, when found, gives <em>ḥayyîm</em> (life) — the foundational gift of the creation (Gen 2:7) and of the covenant (Deut 30:19). "Receives the LORD\'s favor" (<em>wayyāpēq rāṣôn mêyhwh</em>) — to find Wisdom is simultaneously to receive divine favor; Wisdom is the medium through which YHWH\'s grace reaches humanity. The identification of Wisdom\'s gift with YHWH\'s favor is the chapter\'s theological climax.</p>',
    "36": '<p>"But whoever fails to find me harms himself (<em>ḥōṭēʾ nap̄šô</em>, sins against his own nephesh/life); all who hate me embrace death" — <em>ḥōṭēʾ</em> (misses the mark, sins, fails to attain) has both moral and existential weight: missing Wisdom is failing at the fundamental human task. <em>nap̄šô</em> (his own life/soul) — the harm is self-inflicted; rejecting Wisdom is self-destruction by definition, since Wisdom is the order of life. "All who hate me embrace death" (<em>məhābhăbay ʾāhăbû māwet</em>) — the chapter closes on death as the lover of those who hate Wisdom, an inversion of the Wisdom-love relationship (8:17, 21). The rhetorical chiasm is complete: love Wisdom → find life; hate Wisdom → embrace death.</p>'
  },
  "9": {
    "1": '<p>Chapter 9 provides the structural conclusion of the prologue (chapters 1–9) by presenting the two cosmic invitations in parallel: Wisdom\'s banquet (vv. 1–6) and Folly\'s doorstep (vv. 13–18), with intervening instructions (vv. 7–12). "Wisdom has built her house; she has hewn out her seven pillars" — the house-building image echoes 14:1 (the wise woman who builds her house). "Seven pillars" (<em>ʿammudêhā šibʿâ</em>): the number seven is the number of completeness in biblical and ancient Near Eastern symbolism (seven days of creation; seven-branched menorah; seven as the cosmic total). The pillars may represent the complete and well-ordered household; some interpreters see the seven pillars as the seven books of wisdom (Solomonic texts), but the text does not specify. The spaciousness of the seven-pillared house signals Wisdom\'s abundance and hospitality.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"She has slaughtered her animals, mixed her wine, and set her table" — the three acts of banquet preparation (slaughter, wine-mixing, table-setting) follow the pattern of the ancient Near Eastern royal feast. "Mixed her wine" (<em>māzəgâ yênāh</em>) — wine in antiquity was typically mixed with water (and sometimes spices) before drinking; to serve unmixed wine was the exception for special occasions (Song 7:3; Isa 25:6). The deliberate preparation contrasts with the haste and urgency of the Strange Woman\'s offer (7:14–18); Wisdom\'s hospitality is unhurried, complete, and generous. The feast evokes the messianic banquet tradition (Isa 25:6–9).</p>',
    "3": '<p>"She has sent out her servants" (<em>šāləḥâ naʿărōtêhā</em>) — Wisdom\'s servants are the sages, teachers, and parents who transmit her instruction in the community. "Calling from the heights of the city" — the elevated public proclamation of 8:1–4 continues; Wisdom does not simply prepare the feast but actively recruits guests. The sending of servants parallels the royal parable tradition (cf. the parable of the great banquet in Luke 14:16–23 where servants are sent out to invite guests); the invitation is urgent and specific.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"Let the simple come in here" (<em>mî-pétî yāsur hennâ</em>, whoever is simple, turn here!) — the invitation targets <em>pétî</em> (the simple, naive, open person) as the primary audience; the teachable are those most likely to respond. "To the one who lacks understanding (<em>ḥăsar-lēb</em>, lacking heart/mind) she says" — the formula repeats in v. 16 (Folly\'s identical words to the same audience). The structural parallel is deliberate: both Wisdom and Folly call to the same person with nearly the same words. The difference lies in what each offers and where each leads, not in the form of the invitation.</p>',
    "5": '<p>"Come and eat my bread; drink the wine I have mixed" — the bread (<em>laḥmî</em>, my bread) and wine (<em>yênî māzagtî</em>, the wine I have mixed) are both possessives: Wisdom offers what belongs to her. In the ancient world, sharing bread and wine was the most fundamental act of covenant community (cf. Exod 24:11; Gen 14:18). Wisdom\'s feast is a covenant meal, not merely a dinner party; eating with Wisdom is entering her household, her order, her community. The echo of the Passover meal and later Eucharistic imagery is not accidental in the tradition\'s reception history.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"Leave your simple ways and live (<em>ʿizbu pətāʾyîm wihyû</em>)" — the command to "leave" (<em>ʿāzab</em>, to abandon, forsake) naive simplicity uses the same verb for abandoning all sorts of things, including God (Jer 1:16). Life (<em>ḥayyû</em>, live!) is the direct result of leaving simplicity — wisdom-choice is literally life-choice. "Walk in the path of understanding" — <em>ʾašrû bəderek bînâ</em> (make straight your way in the path of understanding) — the spatial metaphor of the two paths reaches its climactic invitation: this is the path, walk in it (cf. Isa 30:21). The prologue\'s entire argument is summarized in one imperative.</p>',
    "7": '<p>Verses 7–12 are often identified as an independent wisdom section inserted between the two banquet scenes. "Whoever rebukes a mocker earns insults" — the practical sociology of wisdom: the <em>lēṣ</em> (mocker/scoffer) is constitutionally closed to correction; rebuking him produces social blowback for the rebuker. "Whoever corrects a wicked man gets hurt" (<em>rāšāʿ</em>) — the wicked person\'s response to correction is violence. This is not defeatism but realistic social intelligence: knowing when rebuke is possible and when it is futile is itself a form of wisdom. Ancient wisdom traditions (Egyptian; Mesopotamian) similarly counsel discernment about which ears will hear.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"Do not rebuke a mocker or he will only hate you" — the negative consequence of rebuking the unreachable is relational: hatred. "Rebuke a wise person and he will love you for it" — the wise person\'s response to correction is the opposite: <em>ʾōhăbeka</em> (he will love you). The asymmetry defines the two categories: the scoffer and the wise are distinguished by their response to rebuke. This is wisdom\'s character-diagnosis: how a person responds to being told they are wrong is the most reliable indicator of their inner formation. The wise embrace correction; the foolish reject it violently.</p>',
    "9": '<p>"Teach the wise and they grow wiser still; instruct the righteous and they gain more" — the paradox of wisdom\'s education: those who already have wisdom receive more when taught; those who have nothing receive nothing from instruction. This is not favoritism but the nature of formative development — only those with the disposition to receive can actually absorb what is given. Ancient education in Israel (and Egypt and Mesopotamia) was selective and cumulative; the scribe\'s training built on prior formation. Wisdom cannot be poured into an unprepared vessel.</p>',
    "10": '<p>"The fear of the LORD is the beginning of wisdom" — the prologue\'s foundational thesis, stated first in 1:7, is restated here as the conclusion of the prologue. <em>ʾăḥēlat ḥokmâ</em> — <em>ʾāḥēlet</em> is the beginning or primary part; in the ancient world this was a qualitative designation (the most fundamental part) as much as a temporal one. "Knowing the Holy One is understanding" (<em>daʿat qədōšîm bînâ</em>) — <em>qədōšîm</em> (Holy One, or Holy Ones — the plural could be a plural of majesty for YHWH or could refer to divine beings) — the encounter with the sacred as the source of discernment. Wisdom is not autonomous human cleverness but participation in the divine life through reverent knowing.</p>',
    "11": '<p>"For through me your days will multiply and years will be added to your life" — long life is the covenantal blessing (Deut 5:16; 6:2; Exod 20:12) promised to those who walk in wisdom and obedience. <em>yarbû lāk yāmêkā</em> (your days will be multiplied) — the promise is quantitative: more days, more years. In the ancient world where life expectancy was dramatically shorter than the modern era and early death was a common experience, the promise of extended life was genuinely significant. Wisdom is not merely qualitative improvement but literal survival advantage — the prudent person navigates dangers that kill the foolish.</p>',
    "12": '<p>"If you are wise, the benefit is yours alone; if you scoff, you alone bear the consequences" — wisdom and its opposite are presented as non-transferable: wisdom\'s benefit accrues to the individual who acquires it; the scoffer\'s ruin falls on himself. This is the wisdom tradition\'s doctrine of individual responsibility — not collective punishment but personal consequence. "You alone bear the consequences" (<em>ûbəlaṣṭôt labbadekā tiśśāʾ</em>) — <em>nāśāʾ</em> (to bear, carry) — the scoffer will carry his own penalty alone. The individualism of the wisdom tradition stands in productive tension with the communal solidarity of the prophetic tradition.</p>',
    "13": '<p>"Dame Folly is loud; she is naive and knows nothing" — <em>ʾešet kəsîlût</em> (the woman of foolishness/Folly) is the structural counterpart to Woman Wisdom of chapters 8–9. She is described as <em>hômiyyâ</em> (loud, tumultuous) — the same word used of the Strange Woman in 7:11. She is <em>pétîyyâ</em> (naive) — using the word for the audience she targets (vv. 4, 16), as if she is only marginally more advanced than those she seduces. "She knows nothing" — <em>biltî yādəʿâ māh</em> (without knowing what) — her ignorance is total, making her teaching the organized transmission of nothingness.</p>',
    "14": '<p>"She sits at the door of her house, in a seat at the high places of the city" — Folly does not descend from her elevated position (the high places, <em>mərōmê qāret</em>) to the streets; she is stationary, waiting. The contrast with Wisdom\'s active movement (going out from her house, sending servants, climbing heights to call) is significant: Folly is passive and opportunistic, not energetically seeking. She occupies the "high places" (<em>bāmôt</em>) — the word also used for the illicit worship sites of Canaanite religion (1 Kgs 12:31; 2 Kgs 17:9), subtly aligning Folly\'s invitation with idolatrous practice.</p>',
    "15": '<p>"Calling out to those who are passing by, going straight on their way" — the people she targets are those <em>məyaššərîm ʾōrəḥôtām</em> (making straight their paths, going directly on their way). They are not drifting or seeking her; they are on course. Folly\'s strategy is interruption and distraction of the purposeful traveler. The Strange Woman of chapter 7 also targeted someone cutting through the street near her corner (7:8); both dangerous figures exploit the ordinary traffic of those going about their business. The danger of folly is not only for the actively searching but for the simply passing-through.</p>',
    "16": '<p>"Let the simple come in here" — the invitation is verbatim from Wisdom\'s invitation (v. 4); the identical words from both callers set up the critical comparison. The paralleling of Wisdom and Folly through identical invitation-language makes the choice between them a matter of discernment, not obviously different appeal. To the naive, the voices may sound the same; only those already formed in wisdom can distinguish the source. This is the prologue\'s final pedagogical move: the formation of the student across chapters 1–9 has been precisely the cultivation of the capacity to distinguish Wisdom from Folly when their words sound alike.</p>',
    "17": '<p>"Stolen water is sweet, and food eaten in secret is delicious" — Folly\'s offer is the appeal of transgression as pleasure. <em>mayim gənûbîm</em> (stolen waters) and <em>leḥem sətārîm</em> (hidden/secret bread) — the pleasure of illicit acquisition adds flavor that lawful goods apparently lack. The psychological insight is acute: prohibition increases desire; secrecy adds excitement. The same dynamic appears in the garden temptation (Gen 3:6, "the tree was desirable"), which Folly\'s invitation deliberately echoes. The offer of the forbidden as the truly satisfying is the archetype of the deceptive invitation in the biblical tradition.</p>',
    "18": '<p>"But he does not know that the dead are there — that her guests are in the depths of Sheol" — the structural parallel with 7:23 (the young man "does not know that his life is the price") closes the prologue with the identical motif: unknowing. Folly\'s house, like the Strange Woman\'s, leads to Sheol. Her guests are <em>rəpāʾîm</em> (the shades, the weakened dead who inhabit the underworld; cf. Isa 26:14; Job 26:5; Ps 88:11) — those who have already fallen and now dwell in death\'s depths. The prologue ends with the fate of Folly\'s guests starkly visible to the reader, even as it remains invisible to the naive person walking through Folly\'s door. The entire nine-chapter prologue has been training the reader to see what the naive cannot.</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'proverbs')
    merge_comm(existing, PROVERBS)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'proverbs', existing)
    print('Proverbs 7–9 mkt-context written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
